)
# GitHub Copilot Prompt:
# Run a placebo DiD using PLACEBO_YEAR as a fake policy date, restricted
# to pre-treatment observations only. Create POST_PLACEBO and did_placebo
# dummies, fit OLS with HC3 errors. An insignificant did_placebo coefficient
# confirms no anticipatory effects.
placebo_panel = pre_panel.copy()
placebo_panel["POST_PLACEBO"] = (placebo_panel["year"] >= PLACEBO_YEAR).astype(int)
placebo_panel["did_placebo"] = placebo_panel["TREATED"] * placebo_panel["POST_PLACEBO"]

placebo_results = smf.ols(
    "employment ~ TREATED + POST_PLACEBO + did_placebo",
    data=placebo_panel,
).fit(cov_type="HC3")

print(placebo_results.summary())
print(
    "Placebo DiD coefficient:",
    placebo_results.params.get("did_placebo"),
    "p=",
    placebo_results.pvalues.get("did_placebo"),
)

# GitHub Copilot Prompt:
# Estimate a two-way fixed effects DiD on the full panel using the formula
# employment ~ did + C(region) + C(year). C(region) absorbs time-invariant
# county differences; C(year) absorbs common annual shocks. The coefficient
# on did is the ATT. Use HC3 robust standard errors.
did_model = smf.ols("employment ~ did + C(region) + C(year)",
                    data=long_panel).fit(cov_type="HC3")
print("\n[Two-Way FE DiD — Full Panel 2018–2025]")
print(did_model.summary())

coef  = did_model.params["did"]
pval  = did_model.pvalues["did"]
ci_lo = did_model.conf_int().loc["did", 0]
ci_hi = did_model.conf_int().loc["did", 1]
sig   = "***" if pval < 0.001 else "**" if pval < 0.01 else "*" if pval < 0.05 else "n.s."

print(f"\n  DiD coefficient : {coef:,.1f} jobs")
print(f"  p-value         : {pval:.4f}  {sig}")
print(f"  95% CI          : [{ci_lo:,.1f}, {ci_hi:,.1f}]")


#4: Interpretation
# The two-way fixed-effects DiD regression indicates that treated Ohio counties experienced approximately 4,000 more manufacturing jobs on average after the 2022 AI grant than would have been expected based on control-region trends. 
# This represents a roughly 13.4\% confidence interval of approximately 3,059 to 4,942 jobs, providing strong evidence that the post-policy employment increase was significantly greater in treated Ohio counties than in comparable Pennsylvania counties.
# The empirical evidence supporting the parallel trends assumption is strong. The pre-treatment slope differential is effectively zero, with an interaction coefficient of approximately –0.6 and a p-value close to 1.000, which means there is no detectable 
# difference in pre-policy employment trends between treated and control counties. 
# The placebo DiD estimate of approximately –3.25 jobs also has a p-value near 0.999, further supporting the absence of anticipatory effects before the policy began. 
# Together, these results strengthen the case that the estimated treatment effect can be interpreted as causal rather than as a reflection of pre-existing differences between Ohio and Pennsylvania counties.
#The positive aggregate employment effect is consistent with the grant’s goal of expanding manufacturing capacity through AI and robotics training. However, the net employment gain likely combines two distinct labor-market forces. 
# On the job-creation side, the subsidy may have increased demand for AI-adjacent roles, such as robotics technicians, 
# precision machine operators, and advanced manufacturing specialists. 
# On the displacement side, routine assembly and manual inspection jobs may have declined as firms adopted new production technologies, potentially reducing opportunities for lower skilled workers despite the increase in  manufacturing.
# The fixed effect design cannot separate these channels because it estimates only the net effect on county-level manufacturing employment. Spatial spillovers may  overestimate treatment effect. For example, if workers migrated from untreated Pennsylvania counties to treated Ohio counties, 
# treated employment would rise while control-region employment would fall, causing the DiD estimator to overstate true net job creation. 
# Future research should break down employment by occupation code and account for cross-county commuting or migration flows to distinguish genuine job creation from geographic reallocation.
